---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Median Calculator",
  description: "Calculate the exact median, average, and range of any dataset instantly. Are outliers skewing your numbers? Find the true middle value now.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a median and how is it different from an average?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The median is the exact middle value in a sorted list of numbers. Half the numbers are higher, and half are lower. The average (mean) is calculated by adding all numbers and dividing by the count. Averages can be heavily skewed by extreme outliers, whereas the median provides a better representation of a 'typical' value in a skewed dataset."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do you calculate the median if there is an even number of items?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "If a dataset has an even number of values, there is no single middle number. To find the median, you must take the two numbers in the middle and calculate their average (add them together and divide by two)."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why do real estate agents use median home prices instead of average?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Real estate markets often have a few extremely expensive mansions that would artificially inflate the average home price. By using the median, the data accurately reflects what a typical buyer might spend in that market, ignoring the extreme high-end outliers."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can the median and mean be the same number?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, if a dataset is perfectly symmetrical (a normal distribution or 'bell curve'), the mean and the median will be exactly the same. They diverge when the data is skewed to one side."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does this calculator handle non-numeric text?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Our calculator automatically filters out any text or special characters. It isolates numerical values (including negative numbers and decimals) regardless of how they are spaced or separated, ensuring accurate computations."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "datePublished": meta.published,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "SiliconBased"
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/median-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Median Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Find the exact middle value and average of your dataset</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="dataSet">Enter your dataset</label>
        <p style="font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Separate numbers by commas, spaces, or newlines.</p>
        <textarea id="dataSet" placeholder="e.g. 10, 20, 30, 40, 50&#10;or&#10;100&#10;200&#10;300"></textarea>
        <div id="data-error" class="error-msg">Please enter at least one valid number.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="results-grid">
        <div class="result-card primary" style="grid-column: 1 / -1; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
          <div class="result-label">Median</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-median">0</div>
        </div>

        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="result-label">Mean (Average)</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-mean">0</div>
        </div>

        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="result-label">Count</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-count">0</div>
        </div>

        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="result-label">Sum</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-sum">0</div>
        </div>

        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="result-label">Min</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-min">0</div>
        </div>

        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="result-label">Max</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-max">0</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Understanding the Median: The True Middle</h2>
      <p>When analyzing data, finding the "average" isn't always enough. In many real-world scenarios, a simple average (the mean) can be incredibly deceptive. Our Median Calculator is designed to instantly parse any dataset, order it, and isolate the exact middle value—protecting your analysis from extreme outliers.</p>

      <h3>The Problem with the "Average" (Mean)</h3>
      <p>The mathematical mean is calculated by adding all the values in a dataset together and dividing by the total number of items. While this is useful, it has a fatal flaw: it is highly sensitive to outliers.</p>
      <p>Imagine a bar with nine people inside, each earning $50,000 a year. The average salary is $50,000. Suddenly, a billionaire walks into the bar. The total income in the room skyrockets. If you calculate the new mean average, it might suggest that the "average" person in the bar makes $100 million a year. This is mathematically true, but practically useless. It does not reflect the reality of almost everyone in the room.</p>
      <p>This is where the <strong>median</strong> comes in.</p>

      <h3>How to Calculate the Median</h3>
      <p>The median is simply the exact middle point of a dataset. To find it, you must first sort all your numbers in ascending order. The method for finding the median changes slightly depending on whether your dataset has an odd or even number of items.</p>

      <h4>Datasets with an Odd Count</h4>
      <p>If you have an odd number of items, finding the median is straightforward. It is the single number sitting perfectly in the center of the sorted list.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dataset:</strong> 12, 5, 22, 10, 8</li>
        <li><strong>Step 1 (Sort):</strong> 5, 8, 10, 12, 22</li>
        <li><strong>Step 2 (Find Middle):</strong> The middle number is 10.</li>
        <li><strong>Median:</strong> 10</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Datasets with an Even Count</h4>
      <p>If you have an even number of items, there is no single middle number. Instead, there are two middle numbers. To find the median, you must calculate the mean average of those two middle numbers.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dataset:</strong> 12, 5, 22, 10, 8, 30</li>
        <li><strong>Step 1 (Sort):</strong> 5, 8, 10, 12, 22, 30</li>
        <li><strong>Step 2 (Find Middle Two):</strong> The middle two numbers are 10 and 12.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 3 (Average):</strong> (10 + 12) &divide; 2 = 11</li>
        <li><strong>Median:</strong> 11</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Common Use Cases for the Median</h3>
      <p>Because the median ignores outliers, it is the preferred metric for central tendency in fields where data is heavily skewed:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Real Estate:</strong> You will almost always hear about "median home prices" rather than average home prices. A few multi-million dollar mansions selling in a month would dramatically pull the average price up, making the market look more expensive than it is for a typical buyer. The median accurately reflects what a standard home costs.</li>
        <li><strong>Income and Salaries:</strong> Government bodies report on median household income for the same reason. Wealth inequality means a small percentage of ultra-high earners significantly skew the average income upward. The median income provides a much more accurate picture of the middle class.</li>
        <li><strong>Software Performance:</strong> When measuring server response times or web performance metrics (like Time to First Byte), developers often look at median response times (the 50th percentile, or P50) rather than the average, because a single stalled network request can severely skew the mean.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Using Our Calculator</h3>
      <p>Our interactive tool makes this process seamless. You do not need to pre-format your data. You can paste numbers separated by commas, spaces, or even new lines from a spreadsheet column. The JavaScript engine instantly parses the text, strips out non-numeric characters, sorts the array, and calculates the true median, mean, and range of your dataset in real-time without sending your data to any external server.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a median and how is it different from an average?</summary>
        <p>The median is the exact middle value in a sorted list of numbers. Half the numbers are higher, and half are lower. The average (mean) is calculated by adding all numbers and dividing by the count. Averages can be heavily skewed by extreme outliers, whereas the median provides a better representation of a "typical" value in a skewed dataset.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do you calculate the median if there is an even number of items?</summary>
        <p>If a dataset has an even number of values, there is no single middle number. To find the median, you must take the two numbers in the middle and calculate their average (add them together and divide by two).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why do real estate agents use median home prices instead of average?</summary>
        <p>Real estate markets often have a few extremely expensive mansions that would artificially inflate the average home price. By using the median, the data accurately reflects what a typical buyer might spend in that market, ignoring the extreme high-end outliers.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can the median and mean be the same number?</summary>
        <p>Yes, if a dataset is perfectly symmetrical (a normal distribution or "bell curve"), the mean and the median will be exactly the same. They diverge when the data is skewed to one side.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does this calculator handle non-numeric text?</summary>
        <p>Our calculator automatically filters out any text or special characters. It isolates numerical values (including negative numbers and decimals) regardless of how they are spaced or separated, ensuring accurate computations.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

    <div class="cross-links">
      Managing business finances? Check out our <a href="/sites/siliconbased/paypal-fee-calculator">PayPal Fee Calculator</a> to figure out exactly how much you need to invoice.
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
      const dataSetInput = document.getElementById('dataSet');
      const dataError = document.getElementById('data-error');

      const resMedian = document.getElementById('res-median');
      const resMean = document.getElementById('res-mean');
      const resCount = document.getElementById('res-count');
      const resSum = document.getElementById('res-sum');
      const resMin = document.getElementById('res-min');
      const resMax = document.getElementById('res-max');

      function formatNumber(num) {
        if (!isFinite(num)) return "0";
        // Convert to max 4 decimal places to avoid floating point weirdness
        return parseFloat(num.toFixed(4)).toString();
      }

      function calculateStats() {
        dataError.style.display = 'none';

        const rawText = dataSetInput.value.trim();
        if (!rawText) {
          resetResults();
          return;
        }

        // Parse numbers: replace all non-numeric characters (except minus and dot) with space, then split
        // This handles commas, newlines, semicolons, tabs, etc.
        const cleanedStr = rawText.replace(/[^0-9.\-eE+]/g, ' ');
        const parts = cleanedStr.split(/\s+/);

        const numbers = [];
        for (let i = 0; i < parts.length; i++) {
          const p = parts[i];
          if (p === '') continue;
          const num = parseFloat(p);
          if (!isNaN(num)) {
            numbers.push(num);
          }
        }

        if (numbers.length === 0) {
          dataError.style.display = 'block';
          dataError.textContent = "No valid numbers found in the input.";
          resetResults();
          return;
        }

        // Calculate Stats
        const count = numbers.length;

        // Sum and Mean
        let sum = 0;
        let min = numbers[0];
        let max = numbers[0];

        for (let i = 0; i < count; i++) {
          const val = numbers[i];
          sum += val;
          if (val < min) min = val;
          if (val > max) max = val;
        }

        const mean = sum / count;

        // Median
        const sorted = numbers.slice().sort((a, b) => a - b);
        let median = 0;
        const mid = Math.floor(count / 2);

        if (count % 2 === 0) {
          // Even count: average of two middle numbers
          median = (sorted[mid - 1] + sorted[mid]) / 2;
        } else {
          // Odd count: middle number
          median = sorted[mid];
        }

        // Display
        resMedian.textContent = formatNumber(median);
        resMean.textContent = formatNumber(mean);
        resCount.textContent = count.toString();
        resSum.textContent = formatNumber(sum);
        resMin.textContent = formatNumber(min);
        resMax.textContent = formatNumber(max);
      }

      function resetResults() {
        resMedian.textContent = "0";
        resMean.textContent = "0";
        resCount.textContent = "0";
        resSum.textContent = "0";
        resMin.textContent = "0";
        resMax.textContent = "0";
      }

      dataSetInput.addEventListener('input', calculateStats);
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }

    .input-group { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .input-group label { display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); }

    textarea { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; font-family: var(--font-mono); resize: vertical; min-height: 150px; }
    textarea:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }

    .error-msg { color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.875rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; display: none; }

    .results-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin-top: 2rem; }
    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .result-card.primary { background: var(--accent-color); color: white; border-color: var(--accent-color); }
    .result-card.primary .result-label { color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.9); }
    .result-card.primary .result-value { color: white; }

    .result-label { font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); word-break: break-word; }

    .explainer { margin-top: 3rem; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer h2 { font-size: 1.75rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); margin-top: 2rem; }
    .explainer h3 { font-size: 1.3rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; color: var(--text-primary); margin-top: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; font-size: 1.05rem; }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 4rem; }
    .faq-section h2 { font-size: 1.75rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); text-align: center; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1.25rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .faq-section details[open] summary { margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .faq-section details p { margin-bottom: 0; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; }

    .cross-links { margin-top: 3rem; padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; text-align: center; }
    .cross-links a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .cross-links a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
